author: @rodrigokuszek
text:
I dont usually comment, but I just wanted to say that somehow, for so long I´ve seen you as an older brother of mine, of all of us. The fact that you had a son and a bit more than a year later I had my own is surreal to me for some reason. I have been watching your videos for so long, it really feels like yesterday when I started to watch you, like back in 2013. And now we are all here. I love the fact that I somehow still feel connected with you, since I believe we have similar humours, we want a quiet life (maybe I dunno) and now we both have a son. 
I dont even know if you will ever read this, but I just wanted to get this out of my chest, so thank you for reading.
It´s been really nice, and we have a lot more up ahead boys.

author: @reermk
text:
Haven't commented for while but I'm really glad you are enjoying japan. As a Japanese, I'm so glad you decided and stay loving japan. There must be something you don't like or didn't like about japan, but for now you seems to be having fun in japan. I'm not a big fan of you, but as a fan, as a subscriber, I really like your home video type of video. simply it feels like sharing happiness of yours and its great. By the way, last time I watched your video was when you moved to japan. Compare to that video, i can see you are adapting to japan,  or more likely getting Japanese. What I meant is that, many Japanese love feeling seasons. Smelling, eating, touching, watching and eating again. Every month we do something related to season. January we celebrate New year and eat mochi, February we give valentine and endure severe cold winter with snow with Setsubun, March we have Ohinasama and ready to have spring with Ume as you did in this video. In April we  celebrate spring, sakura with the start of school(年度）, in May we get extra holidays generally called as "golden week" and get some little vacation with peach flower (momo no ki no hana), in June we get wet with Tsuyu (rainy season)with noisy semi and wait to see summer (vacation). In July we go Natsu matsuri and Hanabi. August we welcome and mourn ancestors with silent semi with smell of kou. In September, these days its still summer, but getting ready for fall season. For example, inakari( harvesting rice), Moon watching, higan bana and kinmokusei is ready to see, sakura trees most likely to change color by this time. In October, there's aki matsuri( fall festival) most likely harvest festival, which comes with kuri, mushrooms and etc. In November we get ready for winter. There's 7 5 3 events, most maples get turn in to red, so sightseeing is one of popular event. In December, its time to ready for Christmas time( more likely eating cake time or date time or Santa time for kids), then ready to end of the year. Generally we tidy up all rooms and ready for food to eat. Some may ready mochi, osechi, to stay in home and watch TV. Some may go to see end of the year live, some may go to temple for 108 bells, some may go to shrine to start dash the new year, some may go higher point to see sun rise. 
Sorry for messaging with such a essay. what I want tell is that, how you are having fun season is really great. Japanese watch, eat and feel every seasons by aging every year with sweet and bitter memories. 
同じ景色に飽きたときには、違う景色を見て、気分転換をするのも良いです。行く場所が見当たらないと思ったら聞いて下さい。
いつでも紹介したい景色があります。拙い英語で申し訳ないです。

Please stop using your child as a prop for your YouTube career. I get that some people think it’s cute, but it’s honestly unethical. author: @パパイヤピスタチオ
text:
日本在住の日本人です。
インバウンドが活発化しており、たくさんの外人が日本に来てますが、ハッキリ言います。外人のせいで日本の治安は劇的に悪化してます。最悪です。
京都では、外人が問題を起こしすぎたせいで、学生の修学旅行先から京都が外れることになりました。生徒たちの一生に一度の大事な思い出が汚されました。
現在、一部の日本人は外人に対して正直ウンザリしてます。私もその内の一人です。
ピューディパイさんのような方であれば大歓迎ですが、もし、日本に来たい、という外人がいたら、日本の文化、歴史に対してきちんと敬意を払ってください。そして問題を起こさないでください。

author: @stoybenxi7395
text: Felix won the world. There was no need to weep, for even as he stared up into the sky, his feet remained planted in the soil. There would be others to take the next step, higher summits would inevitably be trodden, and kings crowned to rule them. He did not need them, he did not need their domain, and their accolades meant little to him. To truly win, he let go. He stayed his feet and remained the man who began the long march. Maybe his son will look back on Pewdiepie videos and wonder how his dad truly changed the world. But to Felix, his world is not so vast. This is his world, here in his arms, on his knee, and it is well won and spent. Live well and prosper my dude.

author: @おしん田倉
text:
日本について好意的な動画を制作してくれるのは有り難いですが、正直、この動画を見て日本に移住しようとか思わないで欲しい。

私は外国人の日本移住を歓迎しません。

スウェーデンも欧州も外国人の移民に破壊されました。
今、日本は見た目では見分けがつかないですが、隣国のあの巨大な国からの移住者が増えており、日本の治安が破壊されつつあります。
彼らは日本人に似ているので日本人になりすますことができる。
日本人の名前を語り、そして完全に日本人になりすましています。

彼らの他にもアラブ人も増えている。
本当に嫌です。

申し訳ないが、皆自分の母国を本当に大事にして欲しい！

私はあの国の人達が日本から出ていくことを望んでいます。

あと日本に移住しようとか思わないでください。

母国を本気で良くしようとして下さい。

author: @JayDeeMC
text:
I really do envy you. I lived in the Tokyo area for 11 years, met my wife there, had a child there, and then moved to Canada for various reasons. We had a second child here in Canada, and just last year, our youngest visited Japan for the first time. Both of my kids are dual citizens, so they can easily live in Japan, even though they don't speak Japanese. My oldest used to be able to, but lost the ability since we moved to Canada when she was 4. She's studying Japanese now, though.

It's always been in the back of my mind that I want to live in Japan again. When we left Japan, I had a job I enjoyed, but we realised that we didn't want our daughter to be educated in Japan. That and my wife didn't want to stay in Japan. We've been in Canada for 9 years now, which I can't believe. There's a good chance that we'll inherit my in-laws' house in the future, which means we'll have a place to live if we decide to move to Japan. Watching Japan vlogs really gives me nostalgic feelings and a sense of longing for my old life. I truly loved living there. Time goes too fast.

Love you.

author: @misaki196
text:
Wow, I'm surprised that you made the decision! I grew up here so I know Japan is a good country, but like any place it has its downsides. Here are some major ones imo:
- Japanese people are generally polite, but it's difficult to make friends with them—especially young Japanese men, often aren’t open to new friendships. My husband has been living in Japan for 14 years and still doesn’t have a single close Japanese male friend. It’s usually easier to befriend Japanese women, but both men and women take longer to become frank and friendly compared to people from other countries. Many of my foreign friends have also struggled to make Japanese friends.
- Japan lacks diversity and isn’t foreigner/minority-friendly in many ways. You'll see this once you live here. You need to be able to speak Japanese to live here comfortably.
- Watch out for cedar pollen allergies! There was a massive cedar plantation project decades ago, but many trees haven’t been left uncut due to a labor shortage. This has led to severe allergy issues, with people in Japan spending over 400 billion yen per year on medical expenses related to cedar pollen allergies.

author: @undeadmasterwitch
text:
I remember when I first discovered Pewdiepie, back in Middle School. I was in a bad mental spot and isolated from most other kids so I always looked forward to watching Pewdiepie's videos after school, even if I barely knew any English then. I've been there for many years, through his Amnesia times, the Funny Montages, his Blue Hair era, the Beard era, Meme Reviews and now I am once again back at his channel, watching his Japan Blogs. This is the best possible outcome that I could've wished for my Childhood Hero.

I am now 23 years old and tomorrow I start my first job. His videos have made me laugh through many dark times in my life and I wish him, his family, his friends and you, whoever is reading this, many good times and that you may have all the love and support throughout the hard times.
Thank you, sincerely.

author: @joshvanderbij4891
text:
Thank you, Felix. You've been a huge part of my life since my late teens 10-11 years ago. When you moved to Japan i was so happy for you and myself too, because i could live vicariously through you in what i perceive to be my true place of belonging. This video has strengthened my recently increasing want to move there, something I've wanted since i started watching you a decade ago after finding anime too. I've made up my mind to just DO IT. Next year, it's happening. I've decided on Osaka, but I LOVE Tokyo too.

Maybe someday, you and i can meet, shake hands (or bow politely), maybe have a drink together, play some darts (my favorite thing to do while going to a bar) and become friends? I'll be looking for some. Who knows.

Anyway. I want to wish you, Marzia, Bjorn and the dogs (rest in peace, Maya) a truly happy, fulfilling life. That your omikujis come out fortunate and that you all stay healthy.

Sincerely, a long time fan of yours.

I used to watch your videos and admire you from the comfort of my home. In my head, you were a far away person and I wanted to become like you.

author: @nnnnnnnnnnn7414
text:
I’m from Taiwan, and I’ve been watching PewDiePie since high school.

His videos have brought me so much joy, and like him, I’ve always had a deep love for Japan. In December 2024, I married my Japanese girlfriend and started a new life in Japan.

My mindset has changed alongside PewDiePie’s videos—just like how he went from screaming at barrels to slowing down and enjoying life. Perhaps one day, we’ll also consider having a cute child.

I just want to say that PewDiePie’s videos always bring back memories of my younger days up until now. I’m truly grateful for his content, and I also appreciate how wholesome and positive the PewDiePie community is.

author: @sarra_tonin
text:
Felix, Marzia, & Bjorn.

These past 3 vlogs have been so incredibly special. They hold a certain emotion within them, that easily explodes externally. I've found myself, borderline crying. These vlogs are so so special to me, it's quiet beautiful. 
They have been with me through some of the most confusing and difficult times in my life, and to see them blossom into what they have been lately, is truly captivating and inspiring.
Thank you so much for allowing us a glimpse into your lives, and mind, as these flourish into something that no words can do justice.

They hold a special place for me to take a moment to sit still, and feel.
Thank you so much.

author: @odyintyr7782
text:
There is just something about these vlogs that is so magical and resonates with me in ways i can't even explain. 
This is what most of us wish in our lifes but can't obtain... We all watched you grow since you were a kid just like us playing videogames everyday without a single care about anything and now here you are. You sir truly achieved the one of the end goals in life in my perspective. I'm about to turn 25 in a month and i've been watching since i was 11, i have been dating my girlfriend for almost 8 years and i truly wish one day i can be in peace and just live my life with my love just like you are here. Not everything is perfect but this content here man... It's something else for me, makes me believe there will be better days and a peaceful future for me. Thank you for bringing this content to the channel, it truly helps and inspires me to keep on living for something greater.

author: @HBanuU
text:
As someone who has grown up and has around multiple times around Asia and Europe due to my parents’ jobs (initially) and then back to my “home country” bc they wanted to be close to family….I would say… its kind of a difficult choice either way (staying or leaving) 
it’s great to grow up in different places abroad, it really opened my eyes and heart to so many things but at the same time I missed a lot of “family time” w like grandparents and having that intimate community growing up, while at the same time my parents moving back “home” did not per se help w that bc I had already made other places my home and separating from there was also hard… so honestly all of it is just difficult. However, one thing that was missed by the generation of my parents when they entered this new “global world”-era was that they didn’t realize how difficult it was for me and my siblings to constantly move while growing up (I’m talking like ages 6, 10, 12 (not like toddler ages or teenage years)) and always having to say goodbye etc and our parents not understanding that due to the fact that they got to spend their childhood in one place/country/home… I understand that it was hard for them to imagine as well but it would have been nice to have that extra care, attention and understanding from my parents who decided to move around so often…
I don’t know what I’m trying to say with this but just wanted to share!

Moving to Japan has been the best choice youve  ever made for yourself buddy.

It gives you the closest to a "normal" life you could have.

In Europe you will always be "pestered" by your celebrity status.

In Japan this seemingly will not happen nearly as much, and therefor also Bjoern will have more of a normal upbringing.

Of course it sucks to be so far off your family and that Bjoerns gradnparents wont be as much a part of his upbringing, but i think that might be a worthwhile trade off.

author: @user-zn8pt8xu7p
text:
42℃？！とても大変でしたね…！私も子供が2人居ますが、同じように熱で夜間救急に行ったことがあります。夜間救急は医師や使える設備も少ないからか、行っても検査できず、1日分の薬をもらって家に帰されました😅ビョルン君が元気になって本当に良かったです😊
あなた達の見る日本は、私がいつも見ている日本より美しくて、新しい発見があります。あなた達家族がどこに住んでいても、応援しています。あなたの動画はどれも大好きです！

42℃?! That must have been really tough! I have two children, and I've had to go to the night emergency due to high fever too. There aren't many doctors or equipment available at night, I guess, so they couldn't do much, and we were sent home with just a day's worth of medicine 😅 I'm so glad Bjorn got better 😊 Japan you see is more beautiful and interesting than what I see in Japan. I support your family, no matter where you live. I love your videos!

author: @lala294
text:
あなたの決断を心から歓迎します！



参考になれば、、
保育園ならポピンズ系列が安心です。セレブ向け保育を行ってきた老舗でとても丁寧に対応してくれます。
幼稚園なら本当は東京都市大学二子幼稚園が昔から有名人のお子さんを預かっており受験を目指している人にはお勧めですが、あなたはそうではないと思います。こどもの自主性を育てたいならモンテッソーリ系列の二子玉川こどものいえも良いと思います。日本では株式会社系（ポピンズの老舗園以外）と無認可はあまりお勧めできません。株式でないモンテッソーリ教育・シュタイナー教育が合っているのではないかなーと思いますので、色々と見学してみてください。（※なぜ株式会社系列がダメのかは、利益追求のために創設されている為人件費が安く良い人材が集まりにくい為です。中にはそうではない所もありますが見抜くのは難しいです。ポピンズさんは質の確保の為に売り手市場の保育士も採用で落とされることがあり、職員教育が徹底しています。）園によってはプレやサマースクール、一時預かりを行っていますので申し込んでみるのも良いと思います。しかし、日本では見学申し込みは基本的に電話になりますので、通訳の方に代わりに電話してもらいながら対応するのが確実だと思います！お父さん、お母さん、がんばって！！応援してます。
☆見学当日は園からNGが出ない限り夫婦とお子さん揃って見学し、担当者との会話や質問などはお母さんが行った方が良いと思います。通訳さんいれば尚良し！お父さんはお子さんを抱っこもしくは歩かせながら周囲の先生（特に先生同士の関係性）や子供の様子をよく観察してください。短い時間の見学では夫婦の役割分担が大切です。違和感があればやめた方が良いと思います。ただ、こちらの勘違いもあるのでその場で直接聞いてしまうのも有りです。
☆今日本人の中で子供の教育の為に軽井沢のある長野県に移住する人が増えています。自然の中で自主性を育む教育に注目が集まっており、あなたならそういう選択肢もあっても良いかもしれません。

Imo, if you miss living in an English speaking country, I would consider Australia or New Zealand. I moved from The Netherlands to the UK recently and a friend went back to Switzerland from the NL.

I understand the pain of being away from family, but considering this I think it's a good decision.

author: @obentoubako
text: Hey pewdiepie, I don't know if you're going to read this, but as a Korean, born and raised in Japan while attending international schools throughout my entire student life, I just wanted to let you know that languages are learnt super naturally for young kids. Although English is my first language, I can very fluently speak Japanese and Korean as well despite having very little formal education on either of those languages. I just wanted to say this because you jokingly mentioned that Bjorn would have to learn 4 languages, but I wanted you to understand that, at least from my experience, I didn't feel like I was "having to learn" 3 languages, as my Japanese and Korean came naturally to me just as English have, although to a lesser degree. I have many other friends with similar experiences that can also speak 2-4 different languages, and I just think that Bjorn is in a super fortunate position to grow up to become multilingual. Anyways, congrats on making the decision to stay, I'm also in a position right now where I'm needing to choose where I want to go and where I want to live, and I understand the feeling of having to decide between being in close proximity of the people and places dear to you, no matter what you end up deciding on.

text:
To everyone with young children: Just remember that before a certain point a fever is good, it's your bodies way of killing the virus. It's really hard, but the fever is natural and good(until it starts really affecting them like altered speech and the like) and if they're acting fine beyond a cough or throwing up they don't always need fever reducers.

Not trying to act like I know everything, but I've been sick a lot in my life and if I take Tylenol or Advil and cold showers I feel like crap, if I wrap myself up to make sure I'm not cold I sleep and feel better quicker, my children as well. My doctor and I agree that medicating too quickly can interfere with the bodies natural defences

author: @AtriasNaradan
text:
Learning more than two languages is generally beneficial for kids intellectual growth. Especially so when it comes to learning more than two very different languages. 

You can research it yourself, but I remember there are researches that says that growing up learning multiple languages trained your brain more to think critically. I think it makes sense because learning different languages is also learning different cultural perspectives. It basically broadens your general point of view. The bigger the difference between languages learnt, the broader your point of view will become, the more critical you're when seeing things. 

Making kids grow up learning to be a polyglot will also make it easier for them to learn better of any other studies later on. Because their brains are already better used to learning.

Happy late birthday to my favorite internet dog. Love you Eggy!! Björn smelling the flowers is too cute. He would have loved smelling those huge flowers at that exhibition lol. He was totally invisible behind that high chair, I can’t believe you found him haha. My 3 year old granddaughter believes she is totally undetectable under a pillow. I’m glad he and Marzia are feeling better. It sucks being sick but it’s a million times worse when it’s your child that is sick. 
I do miss seeing you guys with your friends back in the UK but it’s obvious you are really happy in Japan right now so just enjoy your time together there and if you ever decide to move back you’ll know when it feels right.

author: @HeathPaddles2Far
text:
I love how wholesome this is. it makes me smile watching Pewds grow up and be an incredible father. 

I remember when I was a kid, my dad would take my brother and I out on adventures on Saturday morning. and he would wake us up at like 6am and would tell us to get dressed and be super quiet. he told us that we have to be silent like Ninjas to get out of the house. and that we are going on an adventure. this was his way to get us out of the house. we would often ride our bikes to somewhere to get breakfast. 
this would allow my mom to sleep in till like 8 or 9. and then would often drive over to meet us for breakfast. those were some of my most favorite memories and I really hope more fathers would do the same as well. 😊

author: @itseveryday8600
text:
Pewds, just make plans in case there is a major earthquake around Tokyo. When a huge earth quake hits, they turn school gymnasiums into a local shelter, (because houses will collapse & water electricity may be cut off, so cant stay in the house). These shelters will not let pets stay, so may be forced to leave them at your house, or, some people choose to live in their car with their pet instead ( because there is no other choice). 

A lot of Japanese people have a backpack with emergency amenities ready, e.g torch, sanitary products etc, so when an earth quake comes, they have things ready. Roads could get compromised, and shops unable to open with lack of electricity means you may not be able to purchase necessary products for your family. Also, when you stay in a shelter, people expect you to share things to, they will put pressure on you to give up items that you own, you need plenty of items stocked up. Ideally, you want to avoid staying in a shelter in the first place, as there are a lot of unpleasant things that unfortunately occur in those place, even violence & sexual assualt ( because you end up sharing a roof with people from all walks of life, even criminals), so if you can, have a get away plan, to drive out of Tokyo, to other regions in Japan that were spared by the quake.

author: @rodrigokuszek
text:
I dont usually comment, but I just wanted to say that somehow, for so long I´ve seen you as an older brother of mine, of all of us. The fact that you had a son and a bit more than a year later I had my own is surreal to me for some reason. I have been watching your videos for so long, it really feels like yesterday when I started to watch you, like back in 2013. And now we are all here. I love the fact that I somehow still feel connected with you, since I believe we have similar humours, we want a quiet life (maybe I dunno) and now we both have a son. 
I dont even know if you will ever read this, but I just wanted to get this out of my chest, so thank you for reading.
It´s been really nice, and we have a lot more up ahead boys.

author: @reermk
text:
Haven't commented for while but I'm really glad you are enjoying japan. As a Japanese, I'm so glad you decided and stay loving japan. There must be something you don't like or didn't like about japan, but for now you seems to be having fun in japan. I'm not a big fan of you, but as a fan, as a subscriber, I really like your home video type of video. simply it feels like sharing happiness of yours and its great. By the way, last time I watched your video was when you moved to japan. Compare to that video, i can see you are adapting to japan,  or more likely getting Japanese. What I meant is that, many Japanese love feeling seasons. Smelling, eating, touching, watching and eating again. Every month we do something related to season. January we celebrate New year and eat mochi, February we give valentine and endure severe cold winter with snow with Setsubun, March we have Ohinasama and ready to have spring with Ume as you did in this video. In April we  celebrate spring, sakura with the start of school(年度）, in May we get extra holidays generally called as "golden week" and get some little vacation with peach flower (momo no ki no hana), in June we get wet with Tsuyu (rainy season)with noisy semi and wait to see summer (vacation). In July we go Natsu matsuri and Hanabi. August we welcome and mourn ancestors with silent semi with smell of kou. In September, these days its still summer, but getting ready for fall season. For example, inakari( harvesting rice), Moon watching, higan bana and kinmokusei is ready to see, sakura trees most likely to change color by this time. In October, there's aki matsuri( fall festival) most likely harvest festival, which comes with kuri, mushrooms and etc. In November we get ready for winter. There's 7 5 3 events, most maples get turn in to red, so sightseeing is one of popular event. In December, its time to ready for Christmas time( more likely eating cake time or date time or Santa time for kids), then ready to end of the year. Generally we tidy up all rooms and ready for food to eat. Some may ready mochi, osechi, to stay in home and watch TV. Some may go to see end of the year live, some may go to temple for 108 bells, some may go to shrine to start dash the new year, some may go higher point to see sun rise. 
Sorry for messaging with such a essay. what I want tell is that, how you are having fun season is really great. Japanese watch, eat and feel every seasons by aging every year with sweet and bitter memories. 
同じ景色に飽きたときには、違う景色を見て、気分転換をするのも良いです。行く場所が見当たらないと思ったら聞いて下さい。
いつでも紹介したい景色があります。拙い英語で申し訳ないです。

Please stop using your child as a prop for your YouTube career. I get that some people think it’s cute, but it’s honestly unethical. Bjorn can’t consent to being filmed — he has no understanding of the internet or the fact that you’re sharing his upbringing with millions of strangers. That’s not okay.

Most people agree that family vloggers are among the worst on the platform, yet for some reason, you keep getting a pass. I genuinely don’t understand why.

author: @パパイヤピスタチオ
text:
日本在住の日本人です。
インバウンドが活発化しており、たくさんの外人が日本に来てますが、ハッキリ言います。外人のせいで日本の治安は劇的に悪化してます。最悪です。
京都では、外人が問題を起こしすぎたせいで、学生の修学旅行先から京都が外れることになりました。生徒たちの一生に一度の大事な思い出が汚されました。
現在、一部の日本人は外人に対して正直ウンザリしてます。私もその内の一人です。
ピューディパイさんのような方であれば大歓迎ですが、もし、日本に来たい、という外人がいたら、日本の文化、歴史に対してきちんと敬意を払ってください。そして問題を起こさないでください。

author: @stoybenxi7395
text: Felix won the world. There was no need to weep, for even as he stared up into the sky, his feet remained planted in the soil. There would be others to take the next step, higher summits would inevitably be trodden, and kings crowned to rule them. He did not need them, he did not need their domain, and their accolades meant little to him. To truly win, he let go. He stayed his feet and remained the man who began the long march. Maybe his son will look back on Pewdiepie videos and wonder how his dad truly changed the world. But to Felix, his world is not so vast. This is his world, here in his arms, on his knee, and it is well won and spent. Live well and prosper my dude.

author: @おしん田倉
text:
日本について好意的な動画を制作してくれるのは有り難いですが、正直、この動画を見て日本に移住しようとか思わないで欲しい。

私は外国人の日本移住を歓迎しません。

スウェーデンも欧州も外国人の移民に破壊されました。
今、日本は見た目では見分けがつかないですが、隣国のあの巨大な国からの移住者が増えており、日本の治安が破壊されつつあります。
彼らは日本人に似ているので日本人になりすますことができる。
日本人の名前を語り、そして完全に日本人になりすましています。

彼らの他にもアラブ人も増えている。
本当に嫌です。

申し訳ないが、皆自分の母国を本当に大事にして欲しい！

私はあの国の人達が日本から出ていくことを望んでいます。

あと日本に移住しようとか思わないでください。

母国を本気で良くしようとして下さい。

author: @JayDeeMC
text:
I really do envy you. I lived in the Tokyo area for 11 years, met my wife there, had a child there, and then moved to Canada for various reasons. We had a second child here in Canada, and just last year, our youngest visited Japan for the first time. Both of my kids are dual citizens, so they can easily live in Japan, even though they don't speak Japanese. My oldest used to be able to, but lost the ability since we moved to Canada when she was 4. She's studying Japanese now, though.

It's always been in the back of my mind that I want to live in Japan again. When we left Japan, I had a job I enjoyed, but we realised that we didn't want our daughter to be educated in Japan. That and my wife didn't want to stay in Japan. We've been in Canada for 9 years now, which I can't believe. There's a good chance that we'll inherit my in-laws' house in the future, which means we'll have a place to live if we decide to move to Japan. Watching Japan vlogs really gives me nostalgic feelings and a sense of longing for my old life. I truly loved living there. Time goes too fast.

text: Reminds me of when I was a kid. My dad and my mom but especially my dad would always let me explore and my dad loved explaining the world to me. One time I discovered the sky and the clouds and so i just laid in the yard staring at them since it looked like the sky was moving. Then my dad laid with me and I asked him. Then he explained to me how the sky works in a way a little child could understand. I became deeply fascinated with the sky and space thanks to that. So very cool. I hope to be like my dad and felix if i ever have a kid.

author: @djkoutakutsuma
text: I'm a dad of a 6 year old boy. I'm half Japanese, born and raised in the Philippines, my wife is Filipino - Canadian and I have basic Japanese language proficiency. We went here in Japan for a 2 week vacation back in March 2020 when the pandemic started. We got stuck here and couldn't fly back so we just decided to live here. Now my son will start elementary school next month and so far we have no regrets. Staying here in Japan was the best decision for us. I can definitely relate with how you felt when you were deciding. Enjoy Japan Pewds, been a fan for more than 10 years now. Happy you decided to stay in Japan!

text:
So happy you're staying in Japan; it seems to have a little bit of everything for your family and Björn learning 4 languages might be a good thing.

Also you two are the way my parents were when I was little, a lot of small moments are even learning moments. I loved the smelling flowers part, it was very sweet. I feel like my parents partially homeschooled me while I was in a public school which was great. I mean that in a I had an interest in x so we''d research what we could and go try that. It might be different food that we could try cooking at home then try at a restaurant that has it as a specialty.
